In a hothouse atmosphere so conducive to birth control—the latest wonders of synthetic rubber being now sold throughout the nation—a minority of honest, liberal-minded men like M. Savigny, physician to the principal hospital, and Roland Dorgelès, the great romantic novelist, approve with candor of the whole democratic policy—not only of the right of a woman to abortion, but of the right of women to authority, and thus implicitly, as the internecine war goes on, to a share in the government. One feels the solution tending, in the massive, inevitable, almost majestic way things do, when the force of history once has set them in motion in this old France, in which progress still jostles tradition through streets I love instinctively, venerably as a receptacle of memories.

On a trip to London I was asked by one of the London Sunday papers for some remarks regarding France—a country, of course, absolutely general in its interest, so all my reflections expanded themselves in their tails and kept on coming back regarding the situation in the Empire State of America. I bought newspapers in St. Peter's and became at once as intensely American as an insect in a sugar bowl! Decidedly, the EUropean provinces of the United States looked weird to me at that moment—a Madagascar lounge (we are a nation that invented the fakir couch for ukase of the mind).
